======================================================================
STATISTICAL SIGNIFICANCE TESTS
Thesis: From Accuracy to Profit — F.E. van Riesen (2026)
Option A: Default hyperparameters (max_depth=6, lr=0.05)
======================================================================

Validation set: 35,132 PTU intervals (2024)
Test set      : 35,036 PTU intervals (2025)

--- Per-PTU Cost Difference (Baseline minus Cost-Sensitive) ---
  Mean difference      : €39.41 per PTU
  Std deviation        : €4,812.01
  Median difference    : €0.00
  Intervals where baseline costs more : 17,384 (49.6%)
  Intervals where cost-sensitive costs more : 17,465 (49.8%)
  Total cost reduction (baseline - cost-sensitive): €1,380,834

--- Test 1: Paired t-test (parametric) ---
  H0: Mean per-PTU cost is equal across models
  t-statistic : 1.5331
  p-value     : 0.1253
  Result      : NOT significant at α=0.05 — fail to reject H0
  Note: t-test assumes normality. Imbalance costs have heavy-tailed
        distributions; the Wilcoxon test below is more appropriate.

--- Test 2: Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test (non-parametric) ---
  H0: Median per-PTU cost difference is zero
  W-statistic : 302303394
  p-value     : 0.4826
  Result      : NOT significant at α=0.05 — fail to reject H0
  Note: Non-parametric test, robust to outliers and non-normality.
        Preferred test for heavy-tailed imbalance cost distributions.

--- Normality Check on Cost Differences ---
  Shapiro-Wilk test on sample of 5,000: p=0.0000
  Distribution is NOT normal (p<0.05) → Wilcoxon is appropriate

--- Effect Size ---
  Cohen's d : 0.0082
  Interpretation : negligible effect size

--- Dual vs Single Pricing Breakdown ---
(Asymmetric loss only differs from symmetric in dual-pricing intervals.
 Reductions are expressed as % of |baseline| so the sign is
 interpretable even when baseline cost is negative = BRP revenue.)

